5
00:00:16,174 --> 00:00:19,015
So this talk is about a class that we've both

6
00:00:19,055 --> 00:00:21,696
been running where students make a prototype

7
00:00:22,076 --> 00:00:23,477
every week of the semester.

8
00:00:24,917 --> 00:00:28,038
But it's really about more than just

9
00:00:28,098 --> 00:00:30,219
learning to make prototypes, which

10
00:00:30,259 --> 00:00:31,839
is the main theme of this talk.

11
00:00:34,510 --> 00:00:37,331
So first, some quick introductions to who we are.

12
00:00:37,772 --> 00:00:38,952
I'm Douglas Wilson.

13
00:00:39,132 --> 00:00:41,633
I'm a lecturer at RMIT University in Melbourne,

14
00:00:42,054 --> 00:00:44,835
Australia, where I teach and research game design.

15
00:00:45,375 --> 00:00:47,897
I also co-own a game studio, Degouta Fabrique,

16
00:00:48,337 --> 00:00:49,838
based in Copenhagen, Denmark.

17
00:00:51,338 --> 00:00:52,439
And I'm Bennett Foddy.

18
00:00:52,859 --> 00:00:55,721
I teach at the NYU Game Center, and I make indie games as well,

19
00:00:56,141 --> 00:00:58,582
the most recent of which was Getting Over It with Bennett

20
00:00:58,602 --> 00:00:58,822
Foddy.

21
00:01:01,358 --> 00:01:04,840
In 2014, I started running a class in our master's program

22
00:01:04,860 --> 00:01:08,281
at NYU where students make a digital game every single week

23
00:01:08,301 --> 00:01:09,002
of the semester.

24
00:01:09,482 --> 00:01:12,663
And Doug later adapted it for the bachelor's students

25
00:01:12,723 --> 00:01:13,864
at RMIT in Australia.

26
00:01:14,604 --> 00:01:17,365
So in this talk, we're going to explain why we did that

27
00:01:17,805 --> 00:01:20,487
and how we implemented it and how that turned out.

28
00:01:22,707 --> 00:01:24,628
After my first year teaching at NYU,

29
00:01:24,768 --> 00:01:27,489
I was starting to feel concerned that there was like a handful

30
00:01:27,509 --> 00:01:29,510
of things that I wanted to teach students, that I wanted them

31
00:01:29,550 --> 00:01:30,691
to get from me.

32
00:01:31,214 --> 00:01:33,595
that I couldn't get into a normal style of game

33
00:01:33,616 --> 00:01:34,416
production class.

34
00:01:35,777 --> 00:01:39,661
Students who came to us as very strong coders usually

35
00:01:39,681 --> 00:01:41,202
have been taught to engineer their code

36
00:01:41,262 --> 00:01:42,503
for large-scope projects.

37
00:01:42,543 --> 00:01:44,465
So for small projects, I think that habit

38
00:01:44,525 --> 00:01:48,368
tends to lock them into creative ideas too early in the process,

39
00:01:48,888 --> 00:01:51,190
and it prevents them from experimenting

40
00:01:51,230 --> 00:01:52,932
in the kind of free way that I wanted to see.

41
00:01:53,512 --> 00:01:55,854
But we also get weak coders, weaker coders

42
00:01:56,555 --> 00:01:59,637
with skills in other domains who could work very creatively

43
00:01:59,677 --> 00:02:00,198
and freely.

44
00:02:00,864 --> 00:02:05,526
except that writing code makes the whole process too slow to make fast iteration feasible.

45
00:02:06,107 --> 00:02:11,630
So because of those two problems, students tend to over-commit to their seed ideas

46
00:02:11,810 --> 00:02:16,592
and they spend all of their time building their first idea rather than trying out different ones and seeing which ideas are good.

47
00:02:18,514 --> 00:02:23,056
Because most digital game classes involve students making just one or two projects,

48
00:02:23,536 --> 00:02:29,320
they get very invested in them emotionally and I think that makes it very hard to give the kind of robust critique I want to give.

49
00:02:29,793 --> 00:02:30,893
without discouraging them.

50
00:02:32,074 --> 00:02:34,814
You want to be able to get them to recognize and abandon

51
00:02:34,874 --> 00:02:36,715
unpromising ideas really early on.

52
00:02:37,435 --> 00:02:38,835
But in fact, what happens normally

53
00:02:38,876 --> 00:02:41,656
is you just wind up helping them to make the best of a bad idea.

54
00:02:42,397 --> 00:02:43,737
And that makes it really hard to help

55
00:02:43,777 --> 00:02:47,578
the students build a personal sense of good taste

56
00:02:47,638 --> 00:02:48,478
over time as well.

57
00:02:49,099 --> 00:02:51,659
And I think finally, if you're at school learning game

58
00:02:51,699 --> 00:02:54,520
design, I think making games is homework for you.

59
00:02:54,580 --> 00:02:57,901
And homework generally not as joyful

60
00:02:58,121 --> 00:02:59,482
as a real creative practice.

61
00:02:59,956 --> 00:03:02,457
So I felt like I wanted a class that would address some

62
00:03:02,497 --> 00:03:03,798
of those challenges structurally.

63
00:03:05,899 --> 00:03:07,920
Doug and I are indie game developers.

64
00:03:08,340 --> 00:03:10,361
And the idea that we could solve these problems

65
00:03:10,421 --> 00:03:12,101
by changing the class format comes

66
00:03:12,161 --> 00:03:15,043
from the spirit of rapid prototyping and jamming

67
00:03:15,083 --> 00:03:17,384
that has been prevalent in the indie games community.

68
00:03:17,404 --> 00:03:20,085
And of course, one of the biggest sources

69
00:03:20,125 --> 00:03:22,726
of inspiration for the idea is the Experimental Gameplay

70
00:03:22,766 --> 00:03:25,687
Project, where a group of four CMU students, led by Kyle

71
00:03:26,028 --> 00:03:26,408
Gabler.

72
00:03:27,182 --> 00:03:29,163
made a game prototype every week, more or less,

73
00:03:29,223 --> 00:03:30,304
and posted them online.

74
00:03:31,644 --> 00:03:35,227
And that ran for two semesters in the academic year of 2005.

75
00:03:35,907 --> 00:03:37,328
And it generated a lot of great stuff,

76
00:03:37,388 --> 00:03:39,249
including the prototype for World of Goo,

77
00:03:39,890 --> 00:03:41,431
but was never formalized into a class.

78
00:03:43,012 --> 00:03:43,832
Sorry, go ahead.

79
00:03:44,352 --> 00:03:47,374
More recently, there have been a few popular articles and talks

80
00:03:47,434 --> 00:03:51,257
about Game a Week as a strategy for budding indie game

81
00:03:51,277 --> 00:03:51,777
developers.

82
00:03:52,606 --> 00:03:57,531
So, for example, Rami Ismail, who co-owns the Dutch studio of Lambeer, famously wrote

83
00:03:57,551 --> 00:03:58,432
about Game A Week in 2014.

84
00:03:58,652 --> 00:04:02,176
You can find that article on Gamasutra.

85
00:04:03,377 --> 00:04:09,043
And actually, Rami's post directly inspired a number of game makers, including Ojiro Fumoto,

86
00:04:09,123 --> 00:04:14,870
who went on to make the successful roguelike game Downwell from a Game A Week process.

87
00:04:16,227 --> 00:04:20,269
Also in 2014, Adriel Wallach gave a GDC Europe talk

88
00:04:20,369 --> 00:04:23,350
about Game a Week as an indie dev methodology.

89
00:04:23,830 --> 00:04:25,310
This is actually a really useful talk

90
00:04:25,370 --> 00:04:28,471
that explains the benefits of the Game a Week method,

91
00:04:28,791 --> 00:04:31,412
and I show it to my students in week one of my class.

92
00:04:31,452 --> 00:04:32,772
You can find this online.

93
00:04:35,353 --> 00:04:37,354
Chris DeCaitla has been coordinating

94
00:04:37,374 --> 00:04:39,234
the One Game a Month project on the internet,

95
00:04:39,254 --> 00:04:41,675
which has by now amassed a really large following,

96
00:04:41,815 --> 00:04:44,036
kind of culturally very deeply in indie games.

97
00:04:44,857 --> 00:04:47,439
And I think these sorts of projects show that committing

98
00:04:47,459 --> 00:04:50,400
yourself to a regular cadence of projects is a really great

99
00:04:50,440 --> 00:04:54,042
way to build up speed and also to try out left field ideas

100
00:04:54,122 --> 00:04:57,824
generally and enjoy the process of making video games.

101
00:04:58,524 --> 00:05:01,365
But we had an idea that there could be additional benefits

102
00:05:01,606 --> 00:05:04,207
to that practice in the context of a formal class,

103
00:05:04,907 --> 00:05:06,968
particularly if we added certain additional

104
00:05:07,008 --> 00:05:08,129
pedagogical structures.

105
00:05:10,090 --> 00:05:12,311
So let's look a little bit at how we set it up.

106
00:05:14,487 --> 00:05:18,327
At NYU, the class exists in a two years master's level class,

107
00:05:19,368 --> 00:05:23,288
two years master's level course, which

108
00:05:23,488 --> 00:05:27,969
is limited to students who have already made at least one game

109
00:05:28,009 --> 00:05:32,690
by themselves and demonstrated some basic level of comfort

110
00:05:32,710 --> 00:05:33,330
with their tools.

111
00:05:33,490 --> 00:05:35,191
So I don't want it to be a class about learning

112
00:05:35,811 --> 00:05:37,851
to use Unity or Game Maker or anything like that.

113
00:05:38,591 --> 00:05:40,892
I want it to be about exploring creative ideas.

114
00:05:41,752 --> 00:05:43,592
It's about six hours of class time per week.

115
00:05:44,107 --> 00:05:47,069
About two hours of that is given up to presentations and feedback,

116
00:05:47,489 --> 00:05:48,629
and the rest is just work time.

117
00:05:50,790 --> 00:05:54,772
Students have to submit a playable digital game every week,

118
00:05:55,592 --> 00:05:57,533
and their grade is really heavily penalized

119
00:05:57,573 --> 00:05:58,654
if they miss more than one week.

120
00:05:58,754 --> 00:06:01,335
So there's a lot of social pressure and a lot of structural pressure

121
00:06:01,675 --> 00:06:03,055
to turn something in every week.

122
00:06:05,496 --> 00:06:08,258
And every week's game is produced according to a given prompt

123
00:06:08,438 --> 00:06:11,099
or a constraint, like make a game about rainbows,

124
00:06:11,239 --> 00:06:12,900
or make a game that uses only one button.

125
00:06:13,957 --> 00:06:17,159
Being forced to dream up new ideas is part of the benefit of the class,

126
00:06:17,219 --> 00:06:20,180
so I just want to make sure that they don't just hit up their old notebooks

127
00:06:20,420 --> 00:06:21,821
and remake old ideas.

128
00:06:24,782 --> 00:06:28,283
I tell the students that good work in the context of this class

129
00:06:28,443 --> 00:06:30,824
should answer a particular unanswered question

130
00:06:31,445 --> 00:06:34,746
by testing the value of an original mechanic or an aesthetic design,

131
00:06:35,446 --> 00:06:38,007
by solving a design problem with an existing type of game,

132
00:06:38,388 --> 00:06:41,989
or by seeing if a game can produce a certain original type of experience.

133
00:06:42,658 --> 00:06:45,060
You can't get a good grade just by making Pac-Man.

134
00:06:46,401 --> 00:06:47,602
The games only need to run.

135
00:06:48,142 --> 00:06:49,263
They don't have to be bug-free.

136
00:06:49,303 --> 00:06:51,504
And it's fine if they only work if you play them sort of

137
00:06:51,545 --> 00:06:54,767
generously in a certain way, so long as they form a useful

138
00:06:54,927 --> 00:06:56,688
answer of some kind or a useful test.

139
00:06:57,869 --> 00:07:00,571
And I get them to do all their projects alone as a way of

140
00:07:00,611 --> 00:07:03,413
ensuring that students broaden their skill set and learn new

141
00:07:03,453 --> 00:07:05,294
ways to generate ideas and implement them.

142
00:07:06,074 --> 00:07:06,455
And of course,

143
00:07:07,239 --> 00:07:09,301
There's weeks where nothing comes together,

144
00:07:09,381 --> 00:07:11,403
and the result is a project which runs,

145
00:07:11,463 --> 00:07:13,145
but doesn't really achieve or show anything.

146
00:07:13,766 --> 00:07:15,447
And I make students still, in those cases,

147
00:07:15,508 --> 00:07:17,530
formally present that work, partly

148
00:07:17,550 --> 00:07:20,753
to resist the idea that anyone's process is failure-free,

149
00:07:21,754 --> 00:07:23,496
and partly to share what they learned

150
00:07:23,996 --> 00:07:25,738
from that process of failure with each other.

151
00:07:26,319 --> 00:07:27,860
So that's one crucial way that it

152
00:07:27,920 --> 00:07:30,963
differs from game a week outside of the class format.

153
00:07:33,172 --> 00:07:38,514
All these structures apply a lot of pressure, which is not there in self-imposed game-a-week

154
00:07:39,315 --> 00:07:44,978
structures. So that pressure ensures a very high completion rate, normally close to 100%

155
00:07:45,818 --> 00:07:50,120
of all the projects come in, but it's also really stressful. So to try to relax that pressure

156
00:07:50,661 --> 00:07:55,883
and encourage freedom of experimentation in these students, I only grade them on the best three

157
00:07:55,923 --> 00:08:00,166
prototypes they make over the course of the semester, as selected by me at the end of the

158
00:08:00,186 --> 00:08:00,546
semester.

159
00:08:01,245 --> 00:08:04,668
that emphasizes fast failure and creative risk-taking.

160
00:08:06,909 --> 00:08:09,591
Yeah, so the RMIT version of this.

161
00:08:09,771 --> 00:08:14,235
So in 2016, I took a faculty job at RMIT

162
00:08:14,415 --> 00:08:16,456
and inspired directly by Bennett,

163
00:08:16,696 --> 00:08:18,438
wanted to bring this class format

164
00:08:18,538 --> 00:08:20,419
and evolve it for our program.

165
00:08:21,039 --> 00:08:22,881
So for our first offering that year,

166
00:08:23,101 --> 00:08:24,982
which I coordinated, the class was taught

167
00:08:25,022 --> 00:08:28,044
by our PhD student and local Melbourne Indie,

168
00:08:28,085 --> 00:08:30,306
Michael McMaster, who's in the audience.

169
00:08:30,346 --> 00:08:30,766
Hi, Michael.

170
00:08:31,414 --> 00:08:36,797
So I want to note that the syllabus that I'll share at the end of this talk is actually partially built on Michael's syllabus.

171
00:08:37,558 --> 00:08:41,339
This past year, 2017, Michael and I co-taught the class.

172
00:08:43,281 --> 00:08:48,603
So the class is specifically for second-year undergrads in our game design degree.

173
00:08:48,763 --> 00:08:55,707
So note that this class did not actually include any games programming students who are in a different school and a different degree.

174
00:08:56,668 --> 00:09:00,510
Our students at RMIT Games are mostly visual artists and designers.

175
00:09:01,189 --> 00:09:04,513
And in Australia, you tend to apply to a specific program.

176
00:09:04,913 --> 00:09:07,256
So our students have been taking game classes

177
00:09:08,077 --> 00:09:10,239
and focusing on game classes from day one.

178
00:09:10,800 --> 00:09:12,502
So at this point in the curriculum,

179
00:09:12,702 --> 00:09:14,183
before they take game a week,

180
00:09:14,404 --> 00:09:16,346
they've already taken classes in Game Maker,

181
00:09:16,786 --> 00:09:21,571
and Unity, and 3D art, prototyping, playtesting, and more.

182
00:09:23,119 --> 00:09:26,800
By the way, this year, coming year, we may actually start bringing in some of the

183
00:09:26,840 --> 00:09:30,602
games programming students to join, which would be great, but otherwise Game of

184
00:09:30,622 --> 00:09:37,044
Week is not an elective. It's not open to other degrees. This class, Game of

185
00:09:37,064 --> 00:09:41,666
Week, is actually one of three different streams the students can ballot into, so

186
00:09:41,766 --> 00:09:45,348
only about a third of our students end up taking the class, and they do so

187
00:09:45,428 --> 00:09:49,189
explicitly by choice, which is really important, which we'll talk a little bit

188
00:09:49,229 --> 00:09:49,670
about later.

189
00:09:51,369 --> 00:09:54,051
It's a 24 credit point class, which

190
00:09:54,111 --> 00:09:56,653
means it's about a half their semester workload.

191
00:09:56,693 --> 00:09:58,174
So in essence, Game of Week counts

192
00:09:58,214 --> 00:10:01,075
as like two of their four classes for the semester.

193
00:10:04,418 --> 00:10:07,299
And so it's three hours of seminar plus three hours

194
00:10:07,339 --> 00:10:08,440
of studio per week.

195
00:10:08,920 --> 00:10:11,902
In the three hour seminar, we play all their game submissions

196
00:10:11,942 --> 00:10:15,204
from the previous week, and I do one-on-one feedback meetings.

197
00:10:15,284 --> 00:10:17,546
Me or Michael do one-on-one feedback meetings.

198
00:10:17,933 --> 00:10:23,577
That takes about 90 minutes to get to a class of about 23-ish people.

199
00:10:24,578 --> 00:10:26,900
Then we reveal the new theme for the coming week.

200
00:10:27,580 --> 00:10:32,464
We lecture about relative precedents, like different games or artworks that might relate to the theme.

201
00:10:33,524 --> 00:10:40,009
And finally, give them some time to brainstorm ideas and ask us questions about their ideas.

202
00:10:40,690 --> 00:10:42,971
Later in the week, during the three-hour studio class...

203
00:10:43,675 --> 00:10:46,276
It's just the students working on their games in the lab,

204
00:10:46,657 --> 00:10:48,737
asking us questions and getting feedback

205
00:10:48,837 --> 00:10:50,978
before they actually have to submit the game.

206
00:10:53,459 --> 00:10:57,000
So in our version of the class, a little unlike Bennett's,

207
00:10:57,060 --> 00:10:59,341
students can work alone or in pairs,

208
00:10:59,681 --> 00:11:01,682
but nothing bigger than pairs.

209
00:11:02,162 --> 00:11:03,783
And in fact, we encourage them to try

210
00:11:03,823 --> 00:11:06,924
out different configurations and partners per project

211
00:11:07,024 --> 00:11:08,125
over the course of the semester.

212
00:11:09,577 --> 00:11:12,218
We don't prescribe a preferred technology.

213
00:11:12,678 --> 00:11:14,959
Many of our students use GameMaker or Unity,

214
00:11:15,379 --> 00:11:16,800
which they've learned in previous classes.

215
00:11:16,940 --> 00:11:19,942
But sometimes we also see random alternative technologies.

216
00:11:20,882 --> 00:11:24,444
We do want the students to be making digital games primarily

217
00:11:24,464 --> 00:11:26,625
in this class, although we do occasionally

218
00:11:26,765 --> 00:11:29,826
allow non-digital games if the student can pitch us

219
00:11:29,886 --> 00:11:31,547
on a strong idea for one.

220
00:11:33,583 --> 00:11:37,746
So part of the trick here is to get students assembling their own toolkits

221
00:11:38,087 --> 00:11:41,469
and building off the work of their previous week's submissions.

222
00:11:42,089 --> 00:11:46,492
Students do need to explore a fundamentally new idea each week,

223
00:11:46,752 --> 00:11:50,835
but we explicitly encourage the reuse of scripts and assets and so forth.

224
00:11:52,997 --> 00:11:58,260
This past iteration of the class I had students submit every single week.

225
00:11:58,942 --> 00:12:02,764
mostly because I wanted them to practice scoping and coping even in weeks where

226
00:12:02,784 --> 00:12:07,386
they're super busy and learning how to deal with that. However, as I'll actually

227
00:12:07,406 --> 00:12:12,048
talk a little bit later, I think this policy was a mistake. I think it was a

228
00:12:12,068 --> 00:12:15,570
little too stressful and so this year I'm going to give them one free skip

229
00:12:15,610 --> 00:12:21,033
week at their choice like that does. We grade on three explicit criteria.

230
00:12:22,234 --> 00:12:23,755
functionality and style.

231
00:12:24,035 --> 00:12:26,235
So style is there to emphasize that we want the students

232
00:12:26,255 --> 00:12:28,916
to find their own creative voice through this semester.

233
00:12:29,276 --> 00:12:30,977
And it's something that Michael and I talk about

234
00:12:31,297 --> 00:12:33,597
explicitly in one-on-one feedback meetings.

235
00:12:35,338 --> 00:12:38,479
And like Bennett, we don't grade every single game

236
00:12:38,519 --> 00:12:40,419
for the same reasons Bennett mentioned,

237
00:12:40,539 --> 00:12:43,320
in order to leave room for half-baked prototypes

238
00:12:43,580 --> 00:12:44,200
and failures.

239
00:12:45,521 --> 00:12:48,601
So in the end, we end up grading four of their 11 games

240
00:12:48,661 --> 00:12:49,142
at various.

241
00:12:49,689 --> 00:12:51,450
milestones throughout the semester.

242
00:12:52,290 --> 00:12:55,872
What matters most is that they submit something each week

243
00:12:56,272 --> 00:12:57,493
to avoid abduction.

244
00:12:59,654 --> 00:13:01,455
So there's some cultural differences,

245
00:13:02,016 --> 00:13:04,957
both between bachelors and master students,

246
00:13:05,337 --> 00:13:07,719
and also between American and Australian students.

247
00:13:08,439 --> 00:13:10,120
So we don't do everything exactly the same.

248
00:13:10,841 --> 00:13:13,742
At NYU, in general, I'm trying to avoid

