00:13:13,962 --> 00:13:15,823
showing students sample games.

250
00:13:16,244 --> 00:13:19,125
I think MFAs generally come to us very literate in games.

251
00:13:20,064 --> 00:13:23,485
But when I showed them precedent games every week that were relevant to the theme,

252
00:13:23,665 --> 00:13:27,307
I felt as though I was seeing those games influencing the work more than I wanted.

253
00:13:28,327 --> 00:13:31,708
And I wanted the MFA students to really head out into open water creatively

254
00:13:31,988 --> 00:13:35,530
and to make things outside of established genres, so I stopped doing that.

255
00:13:35,890 --> 00:13:40,191
Yeah, I think really this might actually be the biggest difference between our two classes.

256
00:13:40,311 --> 00:13:45,913
So at RMIT, game a week is a really important place where we can build taste and expose students

257
00:13:45,953 --> 00:13:47,894
to lots and lots of games and artwork.

258
00:13:48,760 --> 00:13:51,965
Each week when we lecture about relevant precedents,

259
00:13:52,405 --> 00:13:55,550
we'll show a video or have a student play the game

260
00:13:55,590 --> 00:13:57,113
on the big screen in front of the class.

261
00:13:57,613 --> 00:13:59,897
So on average, that means we get to talk about

262
00:13:59,997 --> 00:14:01,920
like 10 precedent games or work.

263
00:14:02,400 --> 00:14:07,603
each week. So over the course of the semester, that means we get to show them like over a hundred

264
00:14:07,883 --> 00:14:13,387
relevant games and artworks, which is just a massive amount to be able to expose the students

265
00:14:13,427 --> 00:14:18,750
to, which is really great. In fact, often Michael and I would even pick our weekly prompts based on

266
00:14:18,770 --> 00:14:25,194
the kinds of work that we wanted to expose the students to. By the way, you can see all of

267
00:14:25,534 --> 00:14:31,138
Michael's and my week-by-week lecture notes at the end of our syllabus, which we'll link to at the

268
00:14:31,178 --> 00:14:31,818
end of the talk.

269
00:14:34,026 --> 00:14:35,667
So some other differences.

270
00:14:36,087 --> 00:14:38,828
Bennett has students do brief presentations to the class

271
00:14:39,028 --> 00:14:40,769
and also grades their participation,

272
00:14:41,069 --> 00:14:43,050
for example, when they're playing each other's games.

273
00:14:43,830 --> 00:14:48,192
At RMIT, I removed presentation and participation components.

274
00:14:48,832 --> 00:14:51,773
In my experience as an American working in Australia,

275
00:14:52,373 --> 00:14:55,194
Australian universities tend to emphasize public speaking

276
00:14:55,214 --> 00:14:58,736
a little less compared to comparable American programs.

277
00:14:58,816 --> 00:15:01,497
And so unsurprisingly, our students are pretty anxious

278
00:15:01,717 --> 00:15:02,957
about public speaking.

279
00:15:03,539 --> 00:15:05,280
So the stress of doing Game of Week

280
00:15:05,360 --> 00:15:08,381
is like kind of more than enough in and of itself.

281
00:15:08,481 --> 00:15:11,323
So I wanted to make the class as welcoming as possible.

282
00:15:11,903 --> 00:15:15,544
We do cover public speaking in a number of our other classes,

283
00:15:15,665 --> 00:15:17,745
and I wanted Game of Week to be more focused.

284
00:15:19,866 --> 00:15:22,047
Both of us eliminated all readings and written work

285
00:15:22,067 --> 00:15:23,348
from the class to save on time.

286
00:15:23,368 --> 00:15:25,809
You really are pressed for time as a student in this class.

287
00:15:27,093 --> 00:15:29,954
And at first I got students to give each other feedback

288
00:15:30,054 --> 00:15:31,554
as part of their public presentations

289
00:15:31,594 --> 00:15:33,115
in front of the class, but I found

290
00:15:33,155 --> 00:15:36,395
that that tended to inhibit them from making

291
00:15:36,475 --> 00:15:37,896
personal work or vulnerable work.

292
00:15:38,396 --> 00:15:41,237
And it also resulted in very shallow, useless style

293
00:15:41,257 --> 00:15:43,337
of feedback, given the number of games that we had to see.

294
00:15:43,417 --> 00:15:47,678
So now they get and give feedback in person, one on one,

295
00:15:48,519 --> 00:15:50,919
and only after actually playing each other's games.

296
00:15:52,400 --> 00:15:54,740
Lastly, we both make a.

297
00:15:55,602 --> 00:15:58,843
theatrical, ritualized presentation of the prompt every week.

298
00:15:59,463 --> 00:16:00,944
The first time I ran this class in 2014,

299
00:16:01,764 --> 00:16:04,245
I just told students the creative prompt

300
00:16:04,265 --> 00:16:05,465
at the beginning of the class,

301
00:16:06,205 --> 00:16:08,226
and I think about a third of them every week

302
00:16:08,306 --> 00:16:10,127
would just really phone in their projects.

303
00:16:10,307 --> 00:16:12,908
And I felt as though they had the ability and the interest,

304
00:16:13,168 --> 00:16:15,409
but their whole situation was just a bit too casual.

305
00:16:17,430 --> 00:16:20,871
So I started making a big multimedia reveal of the prompt,

306
00:16:20,931 --> 00:16:21,691
like this video.

307
00:16:22,151 --> 00:16:24,672
The main thing is that it has to show some effort on my part.

308
00:16:25,116 --> 00:16:27,757
to pressure the students to apply a similar amount of effort in their work.

309
00:17:11,427 --> 00:17:14,148
If you haven't got it yet, the prompt for this week,

310
00:17:14,168 --> 00:17:20,069
we'll see in a second, integers.

311
00:17:23,990 --> 00:17:25,590
So after I started doing that, I found

312
00:17:25,610 --> 00:17:28,011
the number of phoned-in projects just dropped almost to zero.

313
00:17:28,191 --> 00:17:29,911
Really, really made an enormous effect.

314
00:17:30,732 --> 00:17:32,452
Sometimes I hide the prompt inside

315
00:17:32,652 --> 00:17:34,412
of a prototype-sized game.

316
00:17:34,572 --> 00:17:37,373
So this is a small game I made with the prompt hidden

317
00:17:37,413 --> 00:17:38,653
at the end of a difficult maze.

318
00:17:39,969 --> 00:17:45,972
And by doing that at least once every year, I hope to kind of indicate the correct scope for a one-week prototype

319
00:17:46,272 --> 00:17:48,073
But also to kind of prove to the students

320
00:17:49,033 --> 00:17:54,496
that prototyping is enjoyable enough that I'll choose just to do it when I don't have to and

321
00:17:54,716 --> 00:17:58,418
Once a semester towards the end of the class when the students are starting to run out of energy

322
00:17:58,438 --> 00:18:06,062
I give each student a personalized prompt in a formal invitation letter that's designed to challenge their personal boundaries

323
00:18:06,302 --> 00:18:07,683
but also importantly

324
00:18:08,384 --> 00:18:11,866
to recognize the artistic identity that they've developed over the course of the class.

325
00:18:12,006 --> 00:18:16,427
So here, the quality of the game that they make out of this prompt isn't the point.

326
00:18:16,908 --> 00:18:20,969
It's to explicitly recognize their individual creative voices.

327
00:18:22,930 --> 00:18:29,193
So like Bennett, we also tried to ritualize the reveal of each prompt at our RMIT class.

328
00:18:29,393 --> 00:18:35,875
So first, we'd show a short teaser video, usually from a film or a TV show or an artwork.

329
00:18:36,935 --> 00:18:39,176
usually something outside of games entirely.

330
00:18:39,196 --> 00:18:41,757
And then we'd have students guess in class

331
00:18:41,777 --> 00:18:43,378
what the prompt might be.

332
00:18:43,718 --> 00:18:46,259
So for example, here for the prompt ritual,

333
00:18:46,579 --> 00:18:49,720
I showed the famous excruciating candle carrying scene

334
00:18:49,800 --> 00:18:51,881
from Tarkovsky's film Nostalgia,

335
00:18:51,921 --> 00:18:53,402
if you've ever seen this.

336
00:18:53,482 --> 00:18:55,362
Yes, I make them watch like the whole nine minutes.

337
00:18:56,623 --> 00:19:00,885
And then we'd reveal the prompt in a nice juicy GIF.

338
00:19:01,525 --> 00:19:03,886
For example, here's that GIF for that prompt ritual.

339
00:19:05,137 --> 00:19:07,757
Another example here is the gift for the theme, Weird Input.

340
00:19:08,277 --> 00:19:10,318
By the way, all these gifts lovingly prepared

341
00:19:10,618 --> 00:19:12,818
by my co-instructor, Michael McMaster.

342
00:19:12,838 --> 00:19:18,360
At RMIT, we also posted the prompt gifts

343
00:19:19,160 --> 00:19:21,921
to the public on social media and encouraged our students

344
00:19:21,961 --> 00:19:26,022
to publicly post their work under the same hashtag,

345
00:19:26,522 --> 00:19:28,962
hashtag game of week 2017 in this case.

346
00:19:29,942 --> 00:19:32,783
So this ritualization and public performance

347
00:19:33,163 --> 00:19:34,063
helps make each week.

348
00:19:34,453 --> 00:19:40,115
seem like something greater and more real than just like a homework assignment for school.

349
00:19:41,255 --> 00:19:45,937
Also, logistically, the hashtag allows students to opt in on their own terms, like whether they

350
00:19:45,997 --> 00:19:50,638
do want to make their work public or not, and gives instructors like me a place to point to

351
00:19:50,678 --> 00:19:55,199
student work without having to play favorites. So instead of feeling pressure to retweet

352
00:19:55,599 --> 00:19:59,940
particular students, I can say, hey, go look at the hashtag that's collected a bunch of students' work.

353
00:20:02,004 --> 00:20:07,305
Another thing that we did to make Game a Week feel more like a community of art practice rather than just another

354
00:20:07,945 --> 00:20:14,928
university class was to arrange a public exhibition of the class games at local Melbourne art game space of Bar SK

355
00:20:15,708 --> 00:20:21,710
So this was opt-in and we had 10 students express interest so Bar SK co-founder and curator

356
00:20:22,430 --> 00:20:25,951
Louis Roots generously reviewed all the students Game a Week

357
00:20:26,716 --> 00:20:29,497
output and picked one game from each student.

358
00:20:29,998 --> 00:20:36,040
The games were then exhibited for two weeks in Collingwood, in Melbourne, in two waves

359
00:20:36,220 --> 00:20:37,381
of five games each.

360
00:20:38,522 --> 00:20:43,964
Note that we explicitly avoided branding the event poster with RMIT University, because

361
00:20:44,144 --> 00:20:48,546
part of the whole goal of Game a Week was for students to find their own artistic voice

362
00:20:48,726 --> 00:20:53,569
and start thinking of themselves as game developers like anyone else out in the real world, rather

363
00:20:53,589 --> 00:20:54,689
than thinking of themselves as just gamers.

364
00:20:55,254 --> 00:20:59,976
students. So this was a nice move that we were really fortunate to be able to do to

365
00:20:59,996 --> 00:21:02,676
kind of take that out of the institution into Melbourne.

366
00:21:04,937 --> 00:21:09,379
One of the nice things about this class structure is the students get so many attempts at coming

367
00:21:09,419 --> 00:21:12,980
up with games that they're more likely to come up with at least one really great idea.

368
00:21:13,700 --> 00:21:18,201
And that often comes after a period of sort of dialing in their process and their ideas

369
00:21:18,241 --> 00:21:20,782
and their taste and developing their artistic voice.

