00:24:24,439 --> 00:24:26,521
Looking beyond the games that come out of the class,

419
00:24:26,861 --> 00:24:29,163
it's also really warmly received by students.

420
00:24:29,667 --> 00:24:31,167
It's always oversubscribed.

421
00:24:31,227 --> 00:24:33,969
The evaluations are consistently really positive.

422
00:24:33,989 --> 00:24:38,391
Here's a couple of pull quotes from the NYU and RMIT student evaluations.

423
00:24:39,352 --> 00:24:42,153
And the vibe in the classroom is really positive.

424
00:24:42,473 --> 00:24:47,256
Students find joy in this kind of ultra small scope work, particularly as they get faster

425
00:24:47,296 --> 00:24:50,717
and the technical challenges of making prototypes starts to fade into the background.

426
00:24:51,918 --> 00:24:55,660
It's important to mention as well, this isn't just a format that works for the most ultra

427
00:24:55,680 --> 00:24:56,460
talented students.

428
00:24:57,444 --> 00:25:02,549
All the students who take it see it as valuable and enjoyable as a class format,

429
00:25:02,709 --> 00:25:05,612
and they think that it improves the quality of their work

430
00:25:06,073 --> 00:25:09,316
and gives them a sort of a taste of enjoying making games.

431
00:25:11,258 --> 00:25:14,642
OK, so to wrap up, some recommendations and acknowledgment

432
00:25:14,662 --> 00:25:16,664
of some challenges with teaching in this format.

433
00:25:18,164 --> 00:25:22,448
So I'm personally really happy about how Game a Week has been working out,

434
00:25:22,569 --> 00:25:23,570
at least at RMIT.

435
00:25:23,850 --> 00:25:26,873
But our students still struggle with semester long projects and

436
00:25:26,893 --> 00:25:27,834
their other classes.

437
00:25:28,314 --> 00:25:31,658
So I think it's important to make sure your curriculum deals with that kind of

438
00:25:31,978 --> 00:25:33,780
project management production skills,

439
00:25:34,261 --> 00:25:36,783
even before a final year capstone project class.

440
00:25:36,803 --> 00:25:40,967
So topping up and pairing Game a Week with also those longer planning skills

441
00:25:41,027 --> 00:25:41,348
classes.

442
00:25:42,881 --> 00:25:47,364
So the pace of Game of Week is probably too fast for students who are still teaching themselves

443
00:25:47,644 --> 00:25:50,226
Unity or 3D modeling or something for the first time.

444
00:25:50,606 --> 00:25:55,550
So I think it's really important that students who take this class be able to get far enough each week so that you can

445
00:25:56,170 --> 00:26:02,695
actually have something to say and critically discuss with them beyond basic like how to use the software questions.

446
00:26:04,030 --> 00:26:05,431
And as I mentioned earlier, a game a week

447
00:26:05,531 --> 00:26:07,292
is one of multiple options for us

448
00:26:07,332 --> 00:26:08,832
that the second year students can take.

449
00:26:09,072 --> 00:26:11,793
And I would not want to make this kind of class mandatory.

450
00:26:12,073 --> 00:26:13,994
It's important to let students know beforehand

451
00:26:14,054 --> 00:26:15,455
how intense this class will be.

452
00:26:15,955 --> 00:26:18,256
And let them take it only if they really feel ready.

453
00:26:22,417 --> 00:26:24,518
The class really is a balancing act

454
00:26:25,038 --> 00:26:27,399
between applying the right amount of pressure

455
00:26:27,859 --> 00:26:30,160
and incentives, and on the other hand,

456
00:26:30,200 --> 00:26:32,361
looking after the students with regard to burnout.

457
00:26:33,401 --> 00:26:40,343
For me, that has meant constantly emphasizing that failures are okay and not punishing people

458
00:26:40,383 --> 00:26:45,124
for weaker submissions and expressing that both verbally every week, but also through

459
00:26:45,144 --> 00:26:46,164
the structure of the class.

460
00:26:47,464 --> 00:26:54,406
For example, we both give feedback verbally, one-on-one, so there's no implicit shaming

461
00:26:54,446 --> 00:26:57,346
involved in public critique.

462
00:26:58,747 --> 00:27:01,287
I alternate between using strict...

463
00:27:01,913 --> 00:27:04,674
highly specified constraints, like make a game with one button,

464
00:27:05,134 --> 00:27:06,595
and vague inspirational themes,

465
00:27:06,635 --> 00:27:09,596
so there's some creative breathing room on alternate weeks.

466
00:27:12,457 --> 00:27:14,258
And I think it's important to push the students,

467
00:27:14,338 --> 00:27:15,818
but you can take it too far.

468
00:27:16,158 --> 00:27:18,259
A game a week can become very stressful,

469
00:27:18,499 --> 00:27:19,740
especially at the end of the semester

470
00:27:19,760 --> 00:27:22,361
as people's final projects in other classes start to ramp up,

471
00:27:22,961 --> 00:27:24,962
and it's really useful to structure in some way

472
00:27:25,002 --> 00:27:28,703
for them to opt out if the schedule is really bad.

473
00:27:31,683 --> 00:27:34,504
So, just wrapping up really quickly, and then we'll be done.

474
00:27:34,884 --> 00:27:38,346
So the most important thing we want to emphasize is that Game a Week,

475
00:27:38,566 --> 00:27:43,348
as a formal class structure, is more than just learning how to work fast and

476
00:27:43,408 --> 00:27:44,128
scope properly.

477
00:27:44,928 --> 00:27:48,890
First, I think Game a Week as a class is also about taste making,

478
00:27:49,430 --> 00:27:52,391
whether that's through explicit lectures about precedence for

479
00:27:52,411 --> 00:27:54,592
the week's theme, like Michael and I do, or

480
00:27:54,632 --> 00:27:57,153
through weekly personal feedback from the instructor.

481
00:27:57,473 --> 00:28:00,955
And I think the sheer volume of games made in Game a Week.

482
00:28:01,698 --> 00:28:03,999
facilitates that kind of a taste evolution.

483
00:28:05,461 --> 00:28:11,225
A huge part of becoming a successful professional artist is learning to take your own work seriously

484
00:28:11,265 --> 00:28:13,087
and hold yourself to a professional standard.

485
00:28:13,787 --> 00:28:17,590
And I think one of the nicest things about this class is that it offers students a chance

